<br>
Erm......actually you're wrong.<br>
<br>
Ion engines are efficient but incredibly slow to build up velocity. Space being as radioactive as it is you want to get to your destination in as short a time as possible. Otherwise your human crew become charcoal burgers.<br>
<br>
Then there is getting off Earth in the first place. Chemical rockets are also distressingly pathetic and barely get 2-4% of their mass into orbit as useful payload. We could get 5 times that figure using nuclear rockets tested back in the 50's!<br>
<br>
Hydrogen is the propellant already used in many rocket motors and the favourite for reactor rockets also. They still need a reaction mass to expel. Fusion IS nuclear power. Thermonuclear fusion is possible now. Pure fusion is not yet possible for useful spaceflight applications and some question whether it ever will be. Solar energy is a joke.<br>
<br>
There is a reason why we haven't been back to the moon in 30 years and only explored it for 3 years. Nothing short of nuclear power can make serious affordable manned spaceflight a reality. Nuclear power isn't an alternative. It's THE alternative. We can't go any further forward without it. Decades have already been wasted dreaming about better technologies we simply don't have. Let's just use what we actually have and change over to something better when it actually exists. <br>
<br>
<br>
 <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

